				<h5 class="card-title">Elephant Social Structure</h5>
				<p class="card-text">
					Elephant social structure is matriarchal, with groups led by the
					oldest female. These tight-knit herds, composed of related females
					and their young, exhibit strong bonds and cooperative behavior.
					Males leave the herd upon maturity, living solitary or forming
					bachelor groups. <span class="read-more-content">
						Communication through vocalizations and touch reinforces their
						social cohesion, vital for navigation, protection, and resource
						sharing. This complex structure underscores their intelligence and
						deep social connections.</span>
				</p>
				<span class="read-more-btn">Read more</span>
				<div class="card-date">Posted on August 6, 2024</div>
